column33: Depending on the player choices in the previous rounds NICO trusted and invested more or less coins. Overall the strategy way cooperative unless otherwise provoked.
column35: See how far I could get NICO to raise its coin wager and then exploit it. But mostly to test out different responses to different playstyles.
column56: Reactions to cooperation and trust in cooperation to NICO.

column33: Cooperation first, rise the stakes, then "cash in" by keeping a high number of coins. Afterwards initialize cooperation strategy again. Also cooperate after human was not cooperative.
column35: Same as above: cooperate, raise the stakes, make one last "keep" when lots of coins are in the pot. Once I figures out that NICO is quite forgiving, I implemented this strategy already at 6 coins from NICO.
column38: Wanting to fond out what NICO would do, but also beating the opponent by having a higher final score.
column56: Trust in a humanoid interaction partner.

column33: He wanted to cooperate rather than compete with me. That's why he almost always returned the entrusted coins.
column35: Most often than not I entrusted 10 coins because I knew that Nico would return them to me. That way I doubled those entrusted coins in score. Sometimes, I kept the Nico's coins to increase my score without thinking too much about Nico's score.

column33: NICO respond quickly with human choice, sometimes maybe mimic.
column35: Entrust less coins at the beginning and keep them, to see NICO's response; entrust more later and return to make coin pool bigger when I think I can trust NICO.
column38: Maximising my earnings while beating NICO as the condition.
column56: Observe people's response when facing unfamiliar robot; see whether one can feel free to enjoy the game with NICO.
column57: Feel very good when playing the mini game with NICO, especially when I noticed that NICO is actually pushing the button using his hand (not a fake shortcut). And  the facial emotion of NICO is also very cute which can alleviate my stress!

column33: During the first rounds of the game, NICO was always returning the coins in a way to make the player get some trust on him. In the second half of the game, if coins were kept by the player, NICO would automatically select just one coin to entrust the player. It would be NICO's main idea to keep the coin he would receive as to maximise its gain. It the player would return the coins, it would update its knowledge on the player and decide to resume returning coins to the player. This procedure would continue if both parties would return the coins entrusted to them. NICO increases the amount of coins entrusted as the player keeps on returning them. I suppose that NICO would keep the coins if the player entrusted 10 (or maybe 9) coins, but I could not get the opportunity to test this hypothesis.
column35: If the number of coins NICO entrusted me were smaller than that I entrusted it, I would automatically return them as a means to gain NICO's trust. This would lead NICO to increase the number of coins entrusted and it would make it return the coins I entrust to it. By the time the quantity entrusted was high enough, e.g., 7 or 8, I decided to keep the coins to myself.
column56: Based on the experiment itself, and especially on the questions of the post-questionnaire, I think the experiment was about the relation of trust in the interaction of humans and robots, and how humans could perceive humanoid robots as trustful.

column33: NICO would keep anything >= 8, and always return <= 7. If I kept his coins then he would entrust only 1 coin the next time and otherwise entrust a random number of coins between 3 and 6. (seems it was a genuine coincidence that I entrusted 8 coins exactly on the 8th round - that put me on the wrong trail it seems)
column35: I started cautiously, but once I noticed that the NICO keeps >=8 coins I would entrust 7 and then 1-3 on the next go (just in case NICO's strategy was to start keeping coins <=7 if I keep it too often) so that I can return my coins without losing many, and entrust 7 again on the next round. Using this strategy I kept NICOs coins low and mine high (even though the task was specifically to maximise your own coins, and NOT to maximise the difference in coins to your opponent). Eventually I risked entrusting 7 coins on consecutive rounds when I inferred that NICO never keeps <=7 coins, even if you've kept them often.
column56: Gauging the effects of NICOs utterances and facial expressions on the participant's gameplay and willingness to trust the NICO with many coins on subsequent rounds, i.e. see if the robot could have emotional influence on the participant.
column57: I think the experimental setup was really well done aesthetically. From a non-scientific perspective, I would have enjoyed the gameplay a bit more if NICO sometimes kept the coins and didn't seem to be so predictable.
